{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"499e7702-a7fa-440d-859c-aa22ec1aac9e","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Since you can exec in:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (convert with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool binary in or use a **sidecar with the SDK image**.\n- For lower overhead in production, consider `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar — it exposes a REST API to collect traces without exec.\n- If you need OS-level detail (native frames, kernel), use **`perf`** instead, but `dotnet-trace` is usually sufficient and much simpler.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ee2b60da-c4e9-41ef-9bff-d3b2bee024f6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question — no code changes or tool usage needed. I'll give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":336,"requestId":"6412:12531F:14F068F:1846E81:69EC155B"},"id":"453fca53-340f-4470-a7a5-79c62014389f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:14:13.080Z","parentId":"1bf3c0f8-4dd6-4f0b-9f1c-7a978ce6501c"}
